    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-28T13:09:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-28T13:09:00-05:00" n="200"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d200">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/5–2754: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 200<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">United States Delegation at the Geneva
                            Conference</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d200fn1">Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_MWP1"
                            >McConaughy</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_DEF1"
                            >Drumright</persName>; revised by <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName>. The last clause in the second sentence appears in
                            <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>’ handwriting on a
                        preliminary draft attached to the source text; the clause originally read,
                        “which is not likely to produce results better than those obtainable by
                            <persName corresp="#p_TH1">Trevelyan</persName>.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-05-28T14:09:00-04:00"
                            >May 28, 1954—2:09 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Tosec 284. Secto 324.<note n="2" xml:id="d200fn2">
                        <ref target="#d199">
                            <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note> It seems clear Chinese Communists are attempting, perhaps
                    with British assistance, to use prisoner issue to bring about direct
                    negotiations between us and Chinese Communists. I have doubts about desirability
                    this course of action, which would probably be given large comment and play in
                    Asia as step toward recognition. Therefore I suggest we should refrain from
                    deputing <pb facs="0465" n="437" xml:id="pg_437"/> representative to negotiate
                    with Chinese Communists—at least pending further efforts by <persName
                        corresp="#p_TH1">Trevelyan</persName>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
